T><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">US</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Florida Nursing Homes Get Temperature Requirements After Hurricane Deaths; Gov. Rick Scott signs two bills into law after a dozen patients died last year</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Florida Gov. Rick Scott signed two bills Monday setting climate requirements for elder-care facilities, something his office has been pushing for since <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/six-dead-at-florida-nursing-home-left-without-power-1505314164">a dozen patients died</ELink> after their nursing home lost central air conditioning during last year's Hurricane Irma.</Para><Para>Under the laws, the state's nearly 3,800 nursing homes and assisted-living facilities must ensure the temperature stays at or below 81 degrees for at least 96 hours after a power outage.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>"The tragedy at the Rehabilitation Center at Hollywood Hills made it clear more needed to be done to ensure the protection of vulnerable Floridians during emergencies like Hurricane Irma," the Republican governor said Monday, referring to the nursing home near Fort Lauderdale where the patients died.</Para><Para>The police in Hollywood have said they are investigating 12 deaths from the nursing home that the local medical examiner determined were homicides caused by environmental heat exposure.</Para><Para>The state suspended the nursing home's license due to the deaths, and the facility is effectively shut down. Julie Allison, co-counsel for the nursing home, which is fighting the shutdown, says actions taken by staff after the hurricane "were more than reasonable in the face of the unprecedented situation."</Para><Para>Before the deaths, elder-care facilities in Florida were required to have enough emergency power for lighting and medical equipment, but not necessarily central air conditioning. The state initially demanded upgrades by mid-November,<ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/florida-nursing-homes-push-back-on-new-rules-after-hurricane-irma-deaths-1508846448"> but the industry balked</ELink>, saying that timeline was unrealistic, and the facilities went to court to press their case.</Para><Para>The state pushed back the requirement to June 1, and in an agreement with industry groups, it said elder-care facilities can seek extensions to Jan. 1, 2019. The agreement between the state and industry also created leeway for on-site storage of generators and fuel.</Para><Para>"It was very important to our members that we had a solution that could be implemented safely and correctly," said Gail Matillo, president of the Florida Senior Living Association, a trade group that tried to block the more aggressive timeline.</Para><Para>June 1 could still prove challenging, but the ability to seek extensions helps, said Steve Bahmer, president and chief executive officer of LeadingAge Florida, which represents 250 nursing homes and other elder-care facilities. He said complying with the rules could cost members anywhere from $350,000 to $7 million, depending on their size.</Para><Para>Federal rules that went into effect in November require nursing homes to have an alternative-energy source to maintain safe temperatures. Those federal rules don't apply to assisted-living facilities, which tend to have less-sick patients than nursing homes.</Para><Para>Write to Jon Kamp at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:jon.kamp@wsj.com">jon.kamp@wsj.com</ELink> and Melanie Evans at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:Melanie.Evans@wsj.com">Melanie.Evans@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Jon Kamp and Melanie Evans </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index